# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: k-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The lower *K*-groups were discovered first, in the sense that adequate descriptions of these groups in terms of other algebraic structures were found.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] For example, if *F* is a field, then *K*0(*F*) is isomorphic to the integers **Z** and is closely related to the notion of vector space dimension.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] For a commutative ring *R*, the group *K*0(*R*) is related to the Picard group of *R*, and when *R* is the ring of integers in a number field, this generalizes the classical construction of the class group.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The group *K*1(*R*) is closely related to the group of units *R*×, and if *R* is a field, it is exactly the group of units.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] For a number field *F*, the group *K*2(*F*) is related to class field theory, the Hilbert symbol, and the solvability of quadratic equations over completions.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In contrast, finding the correct definition of the higher *K*-groups of rings was a difficult achievement of Daniel Quillen, and many of the basic facts about the higher *K*-groups of algebraic varieties were not known until the work of Robert Thomason.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The history of *K*-theory was detailed by Charles Weibel.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In the 19th century, Bernhard Riemann and his student Gustav Roch proved what is now known as the Riemann–Roch theorem.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] If *X* is a Riemann surface, then the sets of meromorphic functions and meromorphic differential forms on *X* form vector spaces.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] A line bundle on *X* determines subspaces of these vector spaces, and if *X* is projective, then these subspaces are finite dimensional.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The Riemann–Roch theorem states that the difference in dimensions between these subspaces is equal to the degree of the line bundle (a measure of twistedness) plus one minus the genus of *X*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In the mid-20th century, the Riemann–Roch theorem was generalized by Friedrich Hirzebruch to all algebraic varieties.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This is a generalization because on a projective Riemann surface, the Euler characteristic of a line bundle equals the difference in dimensions mentioned previously, the Euler characteristic of the trivial bundle is one minus the genus, and the only nontrivial characteristic class is the degree.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The subject of *K*-theory takes its name from a 1957 construction of Alexander Grothendieck which appeared in the Grothendieck–Riemann–Roch theorem, his generalization of Hirzebruch's theorem.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] To each vector bundle on *X*, Grothendieck associates an invariant, its *class*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The set of all classes on *X* was called *K*(*X*) from the German *Klasse*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] By definition, *K*(*X*) is a quotient of the free abelian group on isomorphism classes of vector bundles on *X*, and so it is an abelian group.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] These generators and relations define *K*(*X*), and they imply that it is the universal way to assign invariants to vector bundles in a way compatible with exact sequences.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Grothendieck took the perspective that the Riemann–Roch theorem is a statement about morphisms of varieties, not the varieties themselves.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] He proved that there is a homomorphism from *K*(*X*) to the Chow groups of *X* coming from the Chern character and Todd class of *X*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Additionally, he proved that a proper morphism *f* : *X* → *Y* to a smooth variety *Y* determines a homomorphism *f** : *K*(*X*) → *K*(*Y*) called the *pushforward*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The Grothendieck–Riemann–Roch theorem says that these are equal.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] When *Y* is a point, a vector bundle is a vector space, the class of a vector space is its dimension, and the Grothendieck–Riemann–Roch theorem specializes to Hirzebruch's theorem.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Upon replacing vector bundles by projective modules, *K*0 also became defined for non-commutative rings, where it had applications to group representations.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Atiyah and Hirzebruch quickly transported Grothendieck's construction to topology and used it to define topological K-theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Topological *K*-theory was one of the first examples of an extraordinary cohomology theory: It associates to each topological space *X* (satisfying some mild technical constraints) a sequence of groups *K**n*(*X*) which satisfy all the Eilenberg–Steenrod axioms except the normalization axiom.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The setting of algebraic varieties, however, is much more rigid, and the flexible constructions used in topology were not available.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] While the group *K*0 seemed to satisfy the necessary properties to be the beginning of a cohomology theory of algebraic varieties and of non-commutative rings, there was no clear definition of the higher *K**n*(*X*).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Even as such definitions were developed, technical issues surrounding restriction and gluing usually forced *K**n* to be defined only for rings, not for varieties.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] A group closely related to *K*1 for group rings was earlier introduced by J.H.C.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Henri Poincaré had attempted to define the Betti numbers of a manifold in terms of a triangulation.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] His methods, however, had a serious gap: Poincaré could not prove that two triangulations of a manifold always yielded the same Betti numbers.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] It was clearly true that Betti numbers were unchanged by subdividing the triangulation, and therefore it was clear that any two triangulations that shared a common subdivision had the same Betti numbers.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] What was not known was that any two triangulations admitted a common subdivision.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This hypothesis became a conjecture known as the *Hauptvermutung* (roughly "main conjecture").
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The fact that triangulations were stable under subdivision led J.H.C.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Whitehead to introduce the notion of simple homotopy type.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] A simple homotopy equivalence is defined in terms of adding simplices or cells to a simplicial complex or cell complex in such a way that each additional simplex or cell deformation retracts into a subdivision of the old space.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Part of the motivation for this definition is that a subdivision of a triangulation is simple homotopy equivalent to the original triangulation, and therefore two triangulations that share a common subdivision must be simple homotopy equivalent.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Whitehead proved that simple homotopy equivalence is a finer invariant than homotopy equivalence by introducing an invariant called the *torsion*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The torsion of a homotopy equivalence takes values in a group now called the *Whitehead group* and denoted *Wh*(*π*), where *π* is the fundamental group of the target complex.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Whitehead found examples of non-trivial torsion and thereby proved that some homotopy equivalences were not simple.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The Whitehead group was later discovered to be a quotient of *K*1(**Z***π*), where **Z***π* is the integral group ring of *π*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Later John Milnor used Reidemeister torsion, an invariant related to Whitehead torsion, to disprove the Hauptvermutung.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The first adequate definition of *K*1 of a ring was made by Hyman Bass and Stephen Schanuel.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In topological *K*-theory, *K*1 is defined using vector bundles on a suspension of the space.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] All such vector bundles come from the clutching construction, where two trivial vector bundles on two halves of a space are glued along a common strip of the space.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This gluing data is expressed using the general linear group, but elements of that group coming from elementary matrices (matrices corresponding to elementary row or column operations) define equivalent gluings.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Motivated by this, the Bass–Schanuel definition of *K*1 of a ring *R* is *GL*(*R*) / *E*(*R*), where *GL*(*R*) is the infinite general linear group (the union of all *GL**n*(*R*)) and *E*(*R*) is the subgroup of elementary matrices.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] They also provided a definition of *K*0 of a homomorphism of rings and proved that *K*0 and *K*1 could be fit together into an exact sequence similar to the relative homology exact sequence.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Work in *K*-theory from this period culminated in Bass' book *Algebraic*K*-theory*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In addition to providing a coherent exposition of the results then known, Bass improved many of the statements of the theorems.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Of particular note is that Bass, building on his earlier work with Murthy, provided the first proof of what is now known as the **fundamental theorem of algebraic *K*-theory**.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This is a four-term exact sequence relating *K*0 of a ring *R* to *K*1 of *R*, the polynomial ring *R*[*t*], and the localization *R*[*t*, *t*−1].
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Bass recognized that this theorem provided a description of *K*0 entirely in terms of *K*1.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] By applying this description recursively, he produced negative *K*-groups *K*−n(*R*).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In independent work, Max Karoubi gave another definition of negative *K*-groups for certain categories and proved that his definitions yielded that same groups as those of Bass.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The next major development in the subject came with the definition of *K*2.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Steinberg studied the universal central extensions of a Chevalley group over a field and gave an explicit presentation of this group in terms of generators and relations.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In the case of the group E*n*(*k*) of elementary matrices, the universal central extension is now written St*n*(*k*) and called the *Steinberg group*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In the spring of 1967, John Milnor defined *K*2(*R*) to be the kernel of the homomorphism St(*R*) → *E*(*R*).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The group *K*2 further extended some of the exact sequences known for *K*1 and *K*0, and it had striking applications to number theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This relation is also satisfied by the Hilbert symbol, which expresses the solvability of quadratic equations over local fields.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In particular, John Tate was able to prove that *K*2(**Q**) is essentially structured around the law of quadratic reciprocity.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, several definitions of higher *K*-theory were proposed.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Swan and Gersten both produced definitions of *K**n* for all *n*, and Gersten proved that his and Swan's theories were equivalent, but the two theories were not known to satisfy all the expected properties.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Nobile and Villamayor also proposed a definition of higher *K*-groups.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Karoubi and Villamayor defined well-behaved *K*-groups for all *n*, but their equivalent of *K*1 was sometimes a proper quotient of the Bass–Schanuel *K*1.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Their *K*-groups are now called *KV**n* and are related to homotopy-invariant modifications of *K*-theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Inspired in part by Matsumoto's theorem, Milnor made a definition of the higher *K*-groups of a field.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] He referred to his definition as "purely *ad hoc*", and it neither appeared to generalize to all rings nor did it appear to be the correct definition of the higher *K*-theory of fields.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Much later, it was discovered by Nesterenko and Suslin and by Totaro that Milnor *K*-theory is actually a direct summand of the true *K*-theory of the field.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Specifically, *K*-groups have a filtration called the *weight filtration*, and the Milnor *K*-theory of a field is the highest weight-graded piece of the *K*-theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Additionally, Thomason discovered that there is no analog of Milnor *K*-theory for a general variety.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The first definition of higher *K*-theory to be widely accepted was Daniel Quillen's.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] As part of Quillen's work on the Adams conjecture in topology, he had constructed maps from the classifying spaces *BGL*(**F***q*) to the homotopy fiber of *ψ**q* − 1, where *ψ**q* is the *q*th Adams operation acting on the classifying space *BU*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This map is acyclic, and after modifying *BGL*(**F***q*) slightly to produce a new space *BGL*(**F***q*)+, the map became a homotopy equivalence.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This modification was called the plus construction.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The Adams operations had been known to be related to Chern classes and to *K*-theory since the work of Grothendieck, and so Quillen was led to define the *K*-theory of *R* as the homotopy groups of *BGL*(*R*)+.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Not only did this recover *K*1 and *K*2, the relation of *K*-theory to the Adams operations allowed Quillen to compute the *K*-groups of finite fields.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The classifying space *BGL* is connected, so Quillen's definition failed to give the correct value for *K*0.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Additionally, it did not give any negative *K*-groups.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Since *K*0 had a known and accepted definition it was possible to sidestep this difficulty, but it remained technically awkward.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Conceptually, the problem was that the definition sprung from *GL*, which was classically the source of *K*1.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Because *GL* knows only about gluing vector bundles, not about the vector bundles themselves, it was impossible for it to describe *K*0.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Inspired by conversations with Quillen, Segal soon introduced another approach to constructing algebraic *K*-theory under the name of Γ-objects.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Segal's approach is a homotopy analog of Grothendieck's construction of *K*0.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Where Grothendieck worked with isomorphism classes of bundles, Segal worked with the bundles themselves and used isomorphisms of the bundles as part of his data.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This results in a spectrum whose homotopy groups are the higher *K*-groups (including *K*0).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] However, Segal's approach was only able to impose relations for split exact sequences, not general exact sequences.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In the category of projective modules over a ring, every short exact sequence splits, and so Γ-objects could be used to define the *K*-theory of a ring.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] However, there are non-split short exact sequences in the category of vector bundles on a variety and in the category of all modules over a ring, so Segal's approach did not apply to all cases of interest.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In the spring of 1972, Quillen found another approach to the construction of higher *K*-theory which was to prove enormously successful.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This new definition began with an exact category, a category satisfying certain formal properties similar to, but slightly weaker than, the properties satisfied by a category of modules or vector bundles.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] From this he constructed an auxiliary category using a new device called his "*Q*-construction." Like Segal's Γ-objects, the *Q*-construction has its roots in Grothendieck's definition of *K*0.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Unlike Grothendieck's definition, however, the *Q*-construction builds a category, not an abelian group, and unlike Segal's Γ-objects, the *Q*-construction works directly with short exact sequences.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] If *C* is an abelian category, then *QC* is a category with the same objects as *C* but whose morphisms are defined in terms of short exact sequences in *C*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The *K*-groups of the exact category are the homotopy groups of Ω*BQC*, the loop space of the geometric realization (taking the loop space corrects the indexing).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Quillen additionally proved his "+ = *Q* theorem" that his two definitions of *K*-theory agreed with each other.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This yielded the correct *K*0 and led to simpler proofs, but still did not yield any negative *K*-groups.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] All abelian categories are exact categories, but not all exact categories are abelian.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Because Quillen was able to work in this more general situation, he was able to use exact categories as tools in his proofs.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This technique allowed him to prove many of the basic theorems of algebraic *K*-theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Additionally, it was possible to prove that the earlier definitions of Swan and Gersten were equivalent to Quillen's under certain conditions.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The earliest application of algebraic *K*-theory to topology was Whitehead's construction of Whitehead torsion.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] A closely related construction was found by C.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Wall found that a space *X* dominated by a finite complex has a generalized Euler characteristic taking values in a quotient of *K*0(**Z***π*), where *π* is the fundamental group of the space.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This invariant is called *Wall's finiteness obstruction* because *X* is homotopy equivalent to a finite complex if and only if the invariant vanishes.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Laurent Siebenmann in his thesis found an invariant similar to Wall's that gives an obstruction to an open manifold being the interior of a compact manifold with boundary.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] If two manifolds with boundary *M* and *N* have isomorphic interiors (in TOP, PL, or DIFF as appropriate), then the isomorphism between them defines an *h*-cobordism between *M* and *N*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Whitehead torsion was eventually reinterpreted in a more directly *K*-theoretic way.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This reinterpretation happened through the study of *h*-cobordisms.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Two *n*-dimensional manifolds *M* and *N* are *h*-cobordant if there exists an (*n* + 1)-dimensional manifold with boundary *W* whose boundary is the disjoint union of *M* and *N* and for which the inclusions of *M* and *N* into *W* are homotopy equivalences (in the categories TOP, PL, or DIFF).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Stephen Smale's *h*-cobordism theorem asserted that if *n* ≥ 5, *W* is compact, and *M*, *N*, and *W* are simply connected, then *W* is isomorphic to the cylinder *M* × [0, 1] (in TOP, PL, or DIFF as appropriate).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This theorem proved the Poincaré conjecture for *n* ≥ 5.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] If *M* and *N* are not assumed to be simply connected, then an *h*-cobordism need not be a cylinder.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The *s*-cobordism theorem, due independently to Mazur, Stallings, and Barden, explains the general situation: An *h*-cobordism is a cylinder if and only if the Whitehead torsion of the inclusion *M* ⊂ *W* vanishes.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This generalizes the *h*-cobordism theorem because the simple connectedness hypotheses imply that the relevant Whitehead group is trivial.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In fact the *s*-cobordism theorem implies that there is a bijective correspondence between isomorphism classes of *h*-cobordisms and elements of the Whitehead group.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] An obvious question associated with the existence of *h*-cobordisms is their uniqueness.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The natural notion of equivalence is isotopy.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Jean Cerf proved that for simply connected smooth manifolds *M* of dimension at least 5, isotopy of *h*-cobordisms is the same as a weaker notion called pseudo-isotopy.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Hatcher and Wagoner studied the components of the space of pseudo-isotopies and related it to a quotient of *K*2(**Z***π*).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The proper context for the *s*-cobordism theorem is the classifying space of *h*-cobordisms.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] If *M* is a CAT manifold, then *H*CAT(*M*) is a space that classifies bundles of *h*-cobordisms on *M*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The *s*-cobordism theorem can be reinterpreted as the statement that the set of connected components of this space is the Whitehead group of *π*1(*M*).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This space contains strictly more information than the Whitehead group; for example, the connected component of the trivial cobordism describes the possible cylinders on *M* and in particular is the obstruction to the uniqueness of a homotopy between a manifold and *M* × [0, 1].
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Consideration of these questions led Waldhausen to introduce his algebraic *K*-theory of spaces.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The algebraic *K*-theory of *M* is a space *A*(*M*) which is defined so that it plays essentially the same role for higher *K*-groups as *K*1(**Z**π1(*M*)) does for *M*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In particular, Waldhausen showed that there is a map from *A*(*M*) to a space Wh(*M*) which generalizes the map *K*1(**Z**π1(*M*)) → Wh(*π*1(*M*)) and whose homotopy fiber is a homology theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In order to fully develop *A*-theory, Waldhausen made significant technical advances in the foundations of *K*-theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Waldhausen introduced Waldhausen categories, and for a Waldhausen category *C* he introduced a simplicial category *S*⋅*C* (the *S* is for Segal) defined in terms of chains of cofibrations in *C*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This freed the foundations of *K*-theory from the need to invoke analogs of exact sequences.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Quillen suggested to his student Kenneth Brown that it might be possible to create a theory of sheaves of spectra of which *K*-theory would provide an example.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The sheaf of *K*-theory spectra would, to each open subset of a variety, associate the *K*-theory of that open subset.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Brown developed such a theory for his thesis.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Simultaneously, Gersten had the same idea.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] At a Seattle conference in autumn of 1972, they together discovered a spectral sequence converging from the sheaf cohomology of ${\mathcal {K}}_{n}$ , the sheaf of *K**n*-groups on *X*, to the *K*-group of the total space.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This is now called the Brown–Gersten spectral sequence.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Spencer Bloch, influenced by Gersten's work on sheaves of *K*-groups, proved that on a regular surface, the cohomology group $H^{2}(X,{\mathcal {K}}_{2})$ is isomorphic to the Chow group *CH*2(*X*) of codimension 2 cycles on *X*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Inspired by this, Gersten conjectured that for a regular local ring *R* with fraction field *F*, *K**n*(*R*) injects into *K**n*(*F*) for all *n*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] While progress has been made on Gersten's conjecture since then, the general case remains open.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Lichtenbaum conjectured that special values of the zeta function of a number field could be expressed in terms of the *K*-groups of the ring of integers of the field.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] These special values were known to be related to the étale cohomology of the ring of integers.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Quillen therefore generalized Lichtenbaum's conjecture, predicting the existence of a spectral sequence like the Atiyah–Hirzebruch spectral sequence in topological *K*-theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Quillen's proposed spectral sequence would start from the étale cohomology of a ring *R* and, in high enough degrees and after completing at a prime l invertible in *R*, abut to the l-adic completion of the *K*-theory of *R*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In the case studied by Lichtenbaum, the spectral sequence would degenerate, yielding Lichtenbaum's conjecture.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The necessity of localizing at a prime l suggested to Browder that there should be a variant of *K*-theory with finite coefficients.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] He introduced *K*-theory groups *K**n*(*R*; **Z**/l**Z**) which were **Z**/l**Z**-vector spaces, and he found an analog of the Bott element in topological *K*-theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Soulé used this theory to construct "étale Chern classes", an analog of topological Chern classes which took elements of algebraic *K*-theory to classes in étale cohomology.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Unlike algebraic *K*-theory, étale cohomology is highly computable, so étale Chern classes provided an effective tool for detecting the existence of elements in *K*-theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Dwyer and Eric Friedlander then invented an analog of *K*-theory for the étale topology called étale *K*-theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] For varieties defined over the complex numbers, étale *K*-theory is isomorphic to topological *K*-theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Moreover, étale *K*-theory admitted a spectral sequence similar to the one conjectured by Quillen.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Thomason proved around 1980 that after inverting the Bott element, algebraic *K*-theory with finite coefficients became isomorphic to étale *K*-theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Throughout the 1970s and early 1980s, *K*-theory on singular varieties still lacked adequate foundations.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] While it was believed that Quillen's *K*-theory gave the correct groups, it was not known that these groups had all of the envisaged properties.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] For this, algebraic *K*-theory had to be reformulated.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This was done by Thomason in a lengthy monograph which he co-credited to his dead friend Thomas Trobaugh, who he said gave him a key idea in a dream.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Thomason combined Waldhausen's construction of *K*-theory with the foundations of intersection theory described in volume six of Grothendieck's Séminaire de Géométrie Algébrique du Bois Marie.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] There, *K*0 was described in terms of complexes of sheaves on algebraic varieties.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Thomason discovered that if one worked with in derived category of sheaves, there was a simple description of when a complex of sheaves could be extended from an open subset of a variety to the whole variety.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] By applying Waldhausen's construction of *K*-theory to derived categories, Thomason was able to prove that algebraic *K*-theory had all the expected properties of a cohomology theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Keith Dennis discovered an entirely novel technique for computing *K*-theory based on Hochschild homology.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This was based around the existence of the Dennis trace map, a homomorphism from *K*-theory to Hochschild homology.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] While the Dennis trace map seemed to be successful for calculations of *K*-theory with finite coefficients, it was less successful for rational calculations.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Goodwillie, motivated by his "calculus of functors", conjectured the existence of a theory intermediate to *K*-theory and Hochschild homology.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] He called this theory topological Hochschild homology because its ground ring should be the sphere spectrum (considered as a ring whose operations are defined only up to homotopy).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In the mid-1980s, Bokstedt gave a definition of topological Hochschild homology that satisfied nearly all of Goodwillie's conjectural properties, and this made possible further computations of *K*-groups.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Bokstedt's version of the Dennis trace map was a transformation of spectra *K* → *THH*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This transformation factored through the fixed points of a circle action on *THH*, which suggested a relationship with cyclic homology.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In the course of proving an algebraic *K*-theory analog of the Novikov conjecture, Bokstedt, Hsiang, and Madsen introduced topological cyclic homology, which bore the same relationship to topological Hochschild homology as cyclic homology did to Hochschild homology.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The Dennis trace map to topological Hochschild homology factors through topological cyclic homology, providing an even more detailed tool for calculations.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In 1996, Dundas, Goodwillie, and McCarthy proved that topological cyclic homology has in a precise sense the same local structure as algebraic *K*-theory, so that if a calculation in *K*-theory or topological cyclic homology is possible, then many other "nearby" calculations follow.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The lower *K*-groups were discovered first, and given various ad hoc descriptions, which remain useful.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The functor *K*0 takes a ring *A* to the Grothendieck group of the set of isomorphism classes of its finitely generated projective modules, regarded as a monoid under direct sum.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Any ring homomorphism *A* → *B* gives a map *K*0(*A*) → *K*0(*B*) by mapping (the class of) a projective *A*-module *M* to *M* ⊗*A* *B*, making *K*0 a covariant functor.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] is the map sending every (class of a) finitely generated projective *A*-module *M* to the rank of the free $A_{\mathfrak {p}}$ -module $M_{\mathfrak {p}}$ (this module is indeed free, as any finitely generated projective module over a local ring is free).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This subgroup ${\tilde {K}}_{0}\left(A\right)$ is known as the *reduced zeroth K-theory* of *A*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] If *B* is a ring without an identity element, we can extend the definition of *K*0 as follows.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Let *A* = *B*⊕**Z** be the extension of *B* to a ring with unity obtained by adjoining an identity element (0,1).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] There is a short exact sequence *B* → *A* → **Z** and we define *K*0(*B*) to be the kernel of the corresponding map *K*0(*A*) → *K*0(**Z**) = **Z**.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] An algebro-geometric variant of this construction is applied to the category of algebraic varieties; it associates with a given algebraic variety *X* the Grothendieck's *K*-group of the category of locally free sheaves (or coherent sheaves) on *X*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Given a compact topological space *X*, the topological *K*-theory *K*top(*X*) of (real) vector bundles over *X* coincides with *K*0 of the ring of continuous real-valued functions on *X*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] where the map is induced by projection along the first factor.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The relative *K*0(*A*,*I*) is isomorphic to *K*0(*I*), regarding *I* as a ring without identity.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The independence from *A* is an analogue of the excision theorem in homology.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] If *A* is a commutative ring, then the tensor product of projective modules is again projective, and so tensor product induces a multiplication turning *K*0 into a commutative ring with the class [*A*] as identity.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The exterior product similarly induces a λ-ring structure.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The Picard group embeds as a subgroup of the group of units *K*0(*A*)∗.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] is the direct limit of the $\operatorname {GL} (n)$ , which embeds in $\operatorname {GL} (n+1)$ as the block diagonal matrices with an added 1 entry in the lower right, and $[\operatorname {GL} (A),\operatorname {GL} (A)]$ is its commutator subgroup.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Define an *elementary matrix* to be one which is the sum of an identity matrix and a single off-diagonal element (this is a subset of the elementary matrices used in linear algebra).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Then Whitehead's lemma states that the group $\operatorname {E} (A)$ generated by elementary matrices equals the commutator subgroup $[\operatorname {GL} (A),\operatorname {GL} (A)]$ .
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Indeed, the group $\operatorname {GL} (A)/\operatorname {E} (A)$ was first defined and studied by Whitehead, and is called the **Whitehead group** of the ring A .
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] For a commutative ring A , one can define a determinant ${\displaystyle \det$ to the group of units of A , which vanishes on $\operatorname {E} (A)$ and thus descends to a map $\det :K_{1}(A)\to A^{\times }$ .
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] As $\operatorname {E} (A)\triangleleft \operatorname {SL} (A)$ , one can also define the **special Whitehead group** $SK_{1}(A)=\operatorname {SL} (A)/\operatorname {E} (A)$ .
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The determinant is split by including the group of units $A^{\times }=\operatorname {GL} (1,A)$ into the general linear group $\operatorname {GL} (A)$ , so $K_{1}(A)$ splits as the direct sum of the group of units and the special Whitehead group: $K_{1}(A)\cong A^{\times }\oplus SK_{1}(A)$ .
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] When A is a Euclidean domain (e.g. a field, or the integers) $SK_{1}(A)$ vanishes, and the determinant map is an isomorphism from $K_{1}(A)$ to $A^{\times }$ .
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This is *false* in general for PIDs, thus providing one of the rare mathematical features of Euclidean domains that do not generalize to all PIDs.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] An explicit PID such that $SK_{1}$ is nonzero was given by Ischebeck in 1980 and by Grayson in 1981.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] If A is a Dedekind domain whose quotient field is an algebraic number field (a finite extension of the rationals) then Milnor (1971, corollary 16.3) shows that $SK_{1}(A)$ vanishes.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The vanishing of $SK_{1}(A)$ can be interpreted as saying that $K_{1}$ is generated by the image of $\operatorname {GL} _{1}$ in GL.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] When this fails, one can ask whether $K_{1}$ is generated by the image of $\operatorname {GL} _{2}$ .
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] For a Dedekind domain, this is the case: indeed, $K_{1}$ is generated by the images of $\operatorname {GL} _{1}$ and $\operatorname {SL} _{2}$ in $\operatorname {GL}$ .
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The subgroup of $SK_{1}$ generated by $\operatorname {SL} _{2}$ may be studied by Mennicke symbols.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] For Dedekind domains with all quotients by maximal ideals finite, $SK_{1}$ is a torsion group.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] For a non-commutative ring, the determinant cannot in general be defined, but the map $\operatorname {GL} (A)\to K_{1}(A)$ is a generalisation of the determinant.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] In the case of a central simple algebra A over a field F , the reduced norm provides a generalisation of the determinant giving a map $K_{1}(A)\to F^{\times }$ and $SK_{1}(A)$ may be defined as the kernel.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] **Wang's theorem** states that if A has prime degree then $SK_{1}(A)$ is trivial, and this may be extended to square-free degree.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Wang also showed that $SK_{1}(A)$ is trivial for any central simple algebra over a number field, but Platonov has given examples of algebras of degree prime squared for which $SK_{1}(A)$ is non-trivial.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] John Milnor found the right definition of *K*2: it is the center of the Steinberg group St(*A*) of *A*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] or as the Schur multiplier of the group of elementary matrices.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] For a field, *K*2 is determined by Steinberg symbols: this leads to Matsumoto's theorem.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] One can compute that *K*2 is zero for any finite field.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] and remarked that the proof followed Gauss's first proof of the Law of Quadratic Reciprocity.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] For non-Archimedean local fields, the group *K*2(*F*) is the direct sum of a finite cyclic group of order *m*, say, and a divisible group *K*2(*F*)*m*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] We have *K*2(**Z**) = **Z**/2, and in general *K*2 is finite for the ring of integers of a number field.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] We further have *K*2(**Z**/*n*) = **Z**/2 if *n* is divisible by 4, and otherwise zero.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Matsumoto's original theorem is even more general: For any root system, it gives a presentation for the unstable K-theory.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This presentation is different from the one given here only for symplectic root systems.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] For non-symplectic root systems, the unstable second *K*-group with respect to the root system is exactly the stable *K*-group for GL(*A*).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Unstable second *K*-groups (in this context) are defined by taking the kernel of the universal central extension of the Chevalley group of universal type for a given root system.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This construction yields the kernel of the Steinberg extension for the root systems *A**n* (*n* > 1) and, in the limit, stable second *K*-groups.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] where ***p*** runs over all prime ideals of *A*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] There is a pairing on *K*1 with values in *K*2.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Given commuting matrices *X* and *Y* over *A*, take elements *x* and *y* in the Steinberg group with *X*,*Y* as images.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] For *n* = 0,1,2 these coincide with those below, but for *n* ≧ 3 they differ in general.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The tensor product on the tensor algebra induces a product $K_{m}\times K_{n}\rightarrow K_{m+n}$ making $K_{*}^{M}(F)$ a graded ring which is graded-commutative.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] where $\mu _{m}$ denotes the group of *m*-th roots of unity in some separable extension of *k*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] satisfying the defining relations of the Milnor *K*-group.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Hence $\partial ^{n}$ may be regarded as a map on $K_{n}^{M}(k)$ , called the *Galois symbol* map.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The relation between étale (or Galois) cohomology of the field and Milnor K-theory modulo 2 is the Milnor conjecture, proven by Vladimir Voevodsky.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The analogous statement for odd primes is the Bloch-Kato conjecture, proved by Voevodsky, Rost, and others.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The accepted definitions of higher *K*-groups were given by Quillen (1973), after a few years during which several incompatible definitions were suggested.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Quillen gave two constructions, the "plus-construction" and the "*Q*-construction", the latter subsequently modified in different ways.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The two constructions yield the same *K*-groups.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Here π*n* is a homotopy group, GL(*R*) is the direct limit of the general linear groups over *R* for the size of the matrix tending to infinity, *B* is the classifying space construction of homotopy theory, and the + is Quillen's plus construction.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] He originally found this idea while studying the group cohomology of $GL_{n}(\mathbb {F} _{q})$ and noted some of his calculations were related to $K_{1}(\mathbb {F} _{q})$ .
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Since *BGL*(*R*)+ is path connected and *K*0(*R*) discrete, this definition doesn't differ in higher degrees and also holds for *n* = 0.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The *Q*-construction gives the same results as the +-construction, but it applies in more general situations.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Moreover, the definition is more direct in the sense that the *K*-groups, defined via the *Q*-construction are functorial by definition.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This fact is not automatic in the plus-construction.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] where the first arrow is an admissible epimorphism and the second arrow is an admissible monomorphism.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] is a diagram where the arrow on the left is a covering map (hence surjective) and the arrow on the right is injective.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This category can then be turned into a topological space using the classifying space construction $BQP$ , which is defined to be the geometric realisation of the *nerve* of $QP$ .
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Note the classifying space of a groupoid $B{\mathcal {G}}$ moves the homotopy groups up one degree, hence the shift in degrees for $K_{i}$ being $\pi _{i+1}$ of a space.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This definition coincides with the above definition of *K*0(*P*).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] If *P* is the category of finitely generated projective *R*-modules, this definition agrees with the above *BGL+* definition of *K**n*(*R*) for all *n*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] More generally, for a scheme *X*, the higher *K*-groups of *X* are defined to be the *K*-groups of (the exact category of) locally free coherent sheaves on *X*.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The following variant of this is also used: instead of finitely generated projective (= locally free) modules, take finitely generated modules.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The resulting *K*-groups are usually written *G**n*(*R*).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] When *R* is a noetherian regular ring, then *G*- and *K*-theory coincide.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Indeed, the global dimension of regular rings is finite, i.e. any finitely generated module has a finite projective resolution *P** → *M*, and a simple argument shows that the canonical map *K*0(R) → *G*0(R) is an isomorphism, with [*M*]=Σ ± [*P**n*].
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This isomorphism extends to the higher *K*-groups, too.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] A third construction of *K*-theory groups is the *S*-construction, due to Waldhausen.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] It applies to categories with cofibrations (also called Waldhausen categories).
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] This is a more general concept than exact categories.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] While the Quillen algebraic *K*-theory has provided deep insight into various aspects of algebraic geometry and topology, the *K*-groups have proved particularly difficult to compute except in a few isolated but interesting cases.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Rick Jardine (1993) reproved Quillen's computation using different methods.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Quillen proved that if *A* is the ring of algebraic integers in an algebraic number field *F* (a finite extension of the rationals), then the algebraic *K*-groups of *A* are finitely generated.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Armand Borel used this to calculate *K**i*(*A*) and *K**i*(*F*) modulo torsion.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] The torsion subgroups of *K*2*i*+1(**Z**), and the orders of the finite groups *K*4*k*+2(**Z**) have recently been determined, but whether the latter groups are cyclic, and whether the groups *K*4*k*(**Z**) vanish depends upon Vandiver's conjecture about the class groups of cyclotomic integers.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] See Quillen–Lichtenbaum conjecture for more details.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Algebraic *K*-groups are used in conjectures on special values of L-functions and the formulation of a non-commutative main conjecture of Iwasawa theory and in construction of higher regulators.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Parshin's conjecture concerns the higher algebraic *K*-groups for smooth varieties over finite fields, and states that in this case the groups vanish up to torsion.
[src:k-theory/algebraic-k-theory] Another fundamental conjecture due to Hyman Bass (Bass' conjecture) says that all of the groups *Gn*(*A*) are finitely generated when *A* is a finitely generated **Z**-algebra.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] Bott periodicity can be formulated in numerous ways, with the periodicity in question always appearing as a period-2 phenomenon, with respect to dimension, for the theory associated to the unitary group.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] There are corresponding period-8 phenomena for the matching theories, (real) KO-theory and (quaternionic) KSp-theory, associated to the real orthogonal group and the quaternionic symplectic group, respectively.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] The J-homomorphism is a homomorphism from the homotopy groups of orthogonal groups to stable homotopy groups of spheres, which causes the period 8 Bott periodicity to be visible in the stable homotopy groups of spheres.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] The context of Bott periodicity is that the homotopy groups of spheres, which would be expected to play the basic part in algebraic topology by analogy with homology theory, have proved elusive (and the theory is complicated).
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] The subject of stable homotopy theory was conceived as a simplification, by introducing the suspension (smash product with a circle) operation, and seeing what (roughly speaking) remained of homotopy theory once one was allowed to suspend both sides of an equation as many times as one wished.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] The stable theory was still hard to compute with, in practice.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] What Bott periodicity offered was an insight into some highly non-trivial spaces, with central status in topology because of the connection of their cohomology with characteristic classes, for which all the (*unstable*) homotopy groups could be calculated.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] These spaces are the (infinite, or *stable*) unitary, orthogonal and symplectic groups *U*, *O* and Sp.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] Note that Bott's use of the word *stable* in the title of his seminal paper refers to these stable classical groups and not to stable homotopy groups.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] The important connection of Bott periodicity with the stable homotopy groups of spheres $\pi _{n}^{S}$ comes via the so-called stable *J*-homomorphism from the (unstable) homotopy groups of the (stable) classical groups to these stable homotopy groups $\pi _{n}^{S}$ .
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] Whitehead, it became the subject of the famous Adams conjecture (1963) which was finally resolved in the affirmative by Daniel Quillen (1971).
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] For the theory associated to the infinite unitary group, *U*, the space *BU* is the classifying space for stable complex vector bundles (a Grassmannian in infinite dimensions).
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] One formulation of Bott periodicity describes the twofold loop space, $\Omega ^{2}BU$ of *BU*.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] Here, $\Omega$ is the loop space functor, right adjoint to suspension and left adjoint to the classifying space construction.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] Bott periodicity states that this double loop space is essentially *BU* again; more precisely, $\Omega ^{2}BU\simeq \mathbb {Z} \times BU$ is essentially (that is, homotopy equivalent to) the union of a countable number of copies of *BU*.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] Either of these has the immediate effect of showing why (complex) topological *K*-theory is a 2-fold periodic theory.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] In the corresponding theory for the infinite orthogonal group, *O*, the space *BO* is the classifying space for stable real vector bundles.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] which yields the consequence that *KO*-theory is an 8-fold periodic theory.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] Thus both topological real *K*-theory (also known as *KO*-theory) and topological quaternionic *K*-theory (also known as KSp-theory) are 8-fold periodic theories.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] One elegant formulation of Bott periodicity makes use of the observation that there are natural embeddings (as closed subgroups) between the classical groups.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] The loop spaces in Bott periodicity are then homotopy equivalent to the symmetric spaces of successive quotients, with additional discrete factors of **Z**.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] where the division algebras indicate "matrices over that algebra".
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] As they are 2-periodic/8-periodic, they can be arranged in a circle, where they are called the **Bott periodicity clock** and **Clifford algebra clock**.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] The resulting spaces are homotopy equivalent to the classical reductive symmetric spaces, and are the successive quotients of the terms of the Bott periodicity clock.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] These equivalences immediately yield the Bott periodicity theorems.
[src:k-theory/bott-periodicity-theorem] Bott's original proof (Bott 1959) used Morse theory, which Bott (1956) had used earlier to study the homology of Lie groups.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] In mathematics, in particular in algebraic topology, differential geometry and algebraic geometry, the **Chern classes** are characteristic classes associated with complex vector bundles.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] They have since become fundamental concepts in many branches of mathematics and physics, such as string theory, Chern–Simons theory, knot theory, and Gromov–Witten invariants.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Chern classes were introduced by Shiing-Shen Chern (1946).
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Chern classes are characteristic classes.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] They are topological invariants associated with vector bundles on a smooth manifold.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The question of whether two ostensibly different vector bundles are the same can be quite hard to answer.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The Chern classes provide a simple test: if the Chern classes of a pair of vector bundles do not agree, then the vector bundles are different.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] In topology, differential geometry, and algebraic geometry, it is often important to count how many linearly independent sections a vector bundle has.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The Chern classes offer some information about this through, for instance, the Riemann–Roch theorem and the Atiyah–Singer index theorem.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Chern classes are also feasible to calculate in practice.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] In differential geometry (and some types of algebraic geometry), the Chern classes can be expressed as polynomials in the coefficients of the curvature form.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] There are various ways of approaching the subject, each of which focuses on a slightly different flavor of Chern class.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The original approach to Chern classes was via algebraic topology: the Chern classes arise via homotopy theory which provides a mapping associated with a vector bundle to a classifying space (an infinite Grassmannian in this case).
[src:k-theory/chern-class] In turn, these universal Chern classes can be explicitly written down in terms of Schubert cycles.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] It can be shown that for any two maps *f*, *g* from *M* to the classifying space whose pullbacks are the same bundle *V*, the maps must be homotopic.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Therefore, the pullback by either *f* or *g* of any universal Chern class to a cohomology class of *M* must be the same class.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] This shows that the Chern classes of *V* are well-defined.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Chern's approach used differential geometry, via the curvature approach described predominantly in this article.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] He showed that the earlier definition was in fact equivalent to his.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The resulting theory is known as the Chern–Weil theory.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] There is also an approach of Alexander Grothendieck showing that axiomatically one need only define the line bundle case.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Chern classes arise naturally in algebraic geometry.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The generalized Chern classes in algebraic geometry can be defined for vector bundles (or more precisely, locally free sheaves) over any nonsingular variety.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Algebro-geometric Chern classes do not require the underlying field to have any special properties.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] In particular, the vector bundles need not necessarily be complex.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Regardless of the particular paradigm, the intuitive meaning of the Chern class concerns 'required zeroes' of a section of a vector bundle: for example the theorem saying one can't comb a hairy ball flat (hairy ball theorem).
[src:k-theory/chern-class] See Chern–Simons theory for more discussion.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] An important special case occurs when *V* is a line bundle.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Then the only nontrivial Chern class is the first Chern class, which is an element of the second cohomology group of *X*.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] As it is the top Chern class, it equals the Euler class of the bundle.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The first Chern class turns out to be a complete invariant with which to classify complex line bundles, topologically speaking.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] That is, there is a bijection between the isomorphism classes of line bundles over *X* and the elements of $H^{2}(X;\mathbb {Z} )$ , which associates to a line bundle its first Chern class.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Moreover, this bijection is a group homomorphism (thus an isomorphism): $c_{1}(L\otimes L')=c_{1}(L)+c_{1}(L');$ the tensor product of complex line bundles corresponds to the addition in the second cohomology group.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] In algebraic geometry, this classification of (isomorphism classes of) complex line bundles by the first Chern class is a crude approximation to the classification of (isomorphism classes of) holomorphic line bundles by linear equivalence classes of divisors.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] For complex vector bundles of dimension greater than one, the Chern classes are not a complete invariant.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Given a complex vector bundle *V* of complex rank *n* over a smooth manifold *M,* fix a vector bundle connection $\nabla$ .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Then representatives of each Chern class (also called a **Chern form**) $c_{k}(V)$ of *V* are given as the coefficients of the characteristic polynomial of the curvature form $\Omega$ of $\nabla$ .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The determinant is over the ring of $n\times n$ matrices whose entries are polynomials in *t* with coefficients in the commutative algebra of even-degree complex differential forms on *M*.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The curvature form $\Omega$ of *V* is defined as $\Omega =d\omega +{\frac {1}{2}}[\omega ,\omega ]$ with ω the connection form and *d* the exterior derivative, or via the same expression in which ω is a gauge field for the gauge group of *V*.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The scalar *t* is used here only as an indeterminate to generate the sum from the determinant, and *I* denotes the *n* × *n* identity matrix.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] To say that the expression given is a *representative* of the Chern class indicates that 'class' here means up to addition of an exact differential form.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] That is, Chern classes are cohomology classes in the sense of de Rham cohomology.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] It can be shown that the cohomology classes of the Chern forms do not depend on the choice of connection $\nabla$ .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] One can define a Chern class in terms of an Euler class.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] This is the approach in the book by Milnor and Stasheff, and emphasizes the role of an orientation of a vector bundle.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The basic observation is that a complex vector bundle comes with a canonical orientation, ultimately because $\operatorname {GL} _{n}(\mathbb {C} )$ is connected.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Hence, one simply defines the top Chern class of the bundle to be its Euler class (the Euler class of the underlying real vector bundle) and handles lower Chern classes in an inductive fashion.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The idea is to do base change to get a bundle of one-less rank.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Let $\pi \colon E\to B$ be a complex vector bundle over a paracompact space *B*.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] It then takes some work to check the axioms of Chern classes are satisfied for this definition.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Let $\mathbb {CP} ^{1}$ be the Riemann sphere: 1-dimensional complex projective space.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Suppose that *z* is a holomorphic local coordinate for the Riemann sphere.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Let $V=T\mathbb {CP} ^{1}$ be the bundle of complex tangent vectors having the form $a\partial /\partial z$ at each point, where *a* is a complex number.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] We prove the complex version of the *hairy ball theorem*: *V* has no section which is everywhere nonzero.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] This is evinced by the fact that a trivial bundle always admits a flat connection.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] We must show that this cohomology class is non-zero.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] It suffices to compute its integral over the Riemann sphere: $\int c_{1}={\frac {i}{\pi }}\int {\frac {dz\wedge d{\bar {z}}}{(1+|z|^{2})^{2}}}=2$ after switching to polar coordinates.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] By Stokes' theorem, an exact form would integrate to 0, so the cohomology class is nonzero.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] This proves that $T\mathbb {CP} ^{1}$ is not a trivial vector bundle.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Let *L* be a line in $\mathbb {C} ^{n+1}$ that passes through the origin.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] It is an exercise in elementary geometry to see that the complex tangent space to $\mathbb {C} \mathbb {P} ^{n}$ at the point *L* is naturally the set of linear maps from *L* to its complement.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Thus, the tangent bundle $T\mathbb {C} \mathbb {P} ^{n}$ can be identified with the hom bundle $\operatorname {Hom} ({\mathcal {O}}(-1),\eta )$ where η is the vector bundle such that ${\mathcal {O}}(-1)\oplus \eta ={\mathcal {O}}^{\oplus (n+1)}$ .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] A Chern polynomial is a convenient way to handle Chern classes and related notions systematically.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] This is not a new invariant: the formal variable *t* simply keeps track of the degree of *c**k*(*E*).
[src:k-theory/chern-class] In particular, $c_{t}(E)$ is completely determined by the **total Chern class** of *E*: $c(E)=1+c_{1}(E)+\cdots +c_{n}(E)$ and conversely.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The roots $a_{i}(E)$ , called the **Chern roots** of *E*, determine the coefficients of the polynomial: i.e., $c_{k}(E)=\sigma _{k}(a_{1}(E),\ldots ,a_{n}(E))$ where σ*k* are elementary symmetric polynomials.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] In other words, thinking of *a**i* as formal variables, *c**k* "are" σ*k*.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] A basic fact on symmetric polynomials is that any symmetric polynomial in, say, *t**i*'s is a polynomial in elementary symmetric polynomials in *t**i*'s.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Either by splitting principle or by ring theory, any Chern polynomial $c_{t}(E)$ factorizes into linear factors after enlarging the cohomology ring; *E* need not be a direct sum of line bundles in the preceding discussion.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Let *E* be a vector bundle of rank *r* and $c_{t}(E)=\sum _{i=0}^{r}c_{i}(E)t^{i}$ the Chern polynomial of it.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] We can use these abstract properties to compute the rest of the chern classes of line bundles on $\mathbb {CP} ^{1}$ .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Then using tensor powers, we can relate them to the chern classes of $c_{1}({\mathcal {O}}(n))=n$ for any integer.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Given a complex vector bundle *E* over a topological space *X*, the Chern classes of *E* are a sequence of elements of the cohomology of *X*.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The ***k*-th Chern class** of *E*, which is usually denoted *ck*(*E*), is an element of $H^{2k}(X;\mathbb {Z} ),$ the cohomology of *X* with integer coefficients.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Since the values are in integral cohomology groups, rather than cohomology with real coefficients, these Chern classes are slightly more refined than those in the Riemannian example.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Naturality: If $f:Y\to X$ is continuous and *f*E* is the vector bundle pullback of *E*, then $c_{k}(f^{*}E)=f^{*}c_{k}(E)$ .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Normalization: The total Chern class of the tautological line bundle over $\mathbb {CP} ^{k}$ is 1−*H*, where *H* is Poincaré dual to the hyperplane $\mathbb {CP} ^{k-1}\subseteq \mathbb {CP} ^{k}$ .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] He shows using the Leray–Hirsch theorem that the total Chern class of an arbitrary finite rank complex vector bundle can be defined in terms of the first Chern class of a tautologically defined line bundle.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Namely, introducing the projectivization $\mathbb {P} (E)$ of the rank *n* complex vector bundle *E* → *B* as the fiber bundle on *B* whose fiber at any point $b\in B$ is the projective space of the fiber *Eb*.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The classes $1,a,a^{2},\ldots ,a^{n-1}\in H^{*}(\mathbb {P} (E))$ therefore form a family of ambient cohomology classes restricting to a basis of the cohomology of the fiber.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The Leray–Hirsch theorem then states that any class in $H^{*}(\mathbb {P} (E))$ can be written uniquely as a linear combination of the 1, *a*, *a*2, ..., *a**n*−1 with classes on the base as coefficients.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] One then may check that this alternative definition coincides with whatever other definition one may favor, or use the previous axiomatic characterization.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] In fact, these properties uniquely characterize the Chern classes.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] There is another construction of Chern classes which take values in the algebrogeometric analogue of the cohomology ring, the Chow ring.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Let X be a nonsingular quasi-projective variety of dimension n .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] If $0\to E'\to E\to E''\to 0$ is an exact sequence of vector bundles on X , the Whitney sum formula holds: $c_{t}(E)=c_{t}(E')c_{t}(E'')$ .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] For example, consider a nonsingular quintic threefold in $\mathbb {P} ^{4}$ .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Let h denote the hyperplane class in $A^{\bullet }(X)$ .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Since the Chow ring of a hypersurface is difficult to compute, we will consider this sequence as a sequence of coherent sheaves in $\mathbb {P} ^{4}$ .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Using the Gauss-Bonnet theorem we can integrate the class $c_{3}({\mathcal {T}}_{X})$ to compute the Euler characteristic.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Traditionally this is called the Euler class.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The Euler characteristic can then be used to compute the Betti numbers for the cohomology of X by using the definition of the Euler characteristic and using the Lefschetz hyperplane theorem.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] In particular, we can find X is a spin 4-manifold if $4-d$ is even, so every smooth hypersurface of degree $2k$ is a spin manifold.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] Chern classes can be used to construct a homomorphism of rings from the topological K-theory of a space to (the completion of) its rational cohomology.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] This last expression, justified by invoking the splitting principle, is taken as the definition *ch(V)* for arbitrary vector bundles *V*.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The Chern character is useful in part because it facilitates the computation of the Chern class of a tensor product.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] As stated above, using the Grothendieck additivity axiom for Chern classes, the first of these identities can be generalized to state that *ch* is a homomorphism of abelian groups from the K-theory *K*(*X*) into the rational cohomology of *X*.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The second identity establishes the fact that this homomorphism also respects products in *K*(*X*), and so *ch* is a homomorphism of rings.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The Chern character is used in the Hirzebruch–Riemann–Roch theorem.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] For example, if the manifold has dimension 6, there are three linearly independent Chern numbers, given by $c_{1}^{3}$ , $c_{1}c_{2}$ , and $c_{3}$ .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] In general, if the manifold has dimension $2n$ , the number of possible independent Chern numbers is the number of partitions of n .
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The Chern numbers of the tangent bundle of a complex (or almost complex) manifold are called the Chern numbers of the manifold, and are important invariants.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] There is a generalization of the theory of Chern classes, where ordinary cohomology is replaced with a generalized cohomology theory.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The theories for which such generalization is possible are called *complex orientable*.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The formal properties of the Chern classes remain the same, with one crucial difference: the rule which computes the first Chern class of a tensor product of line bundles in terms of first Chern classes of the factors is not (ordinary) addition, but rather a formal group law.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] In algebraic geometry there is a similar theory of Chern classes of vector bundles.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The theory of Chern classes gives rise to cobordism invariants for almost complex manifolds.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] If *M* is an almost complex manifold, then its tangent bundle is a complex vector bundle.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The **Chern classes** of *M* are thus defined to be the Chern classes of its tangent bundle.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] If *M* is also compact and of dimension 2*d*, then each monomial of total degree 2*d* in the Chern classes can be paired with the fundamental class of *M*, giving an integer, a **Chern number** of *M*.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] If *M*′ is another almost complex manifold of the same dimension, then it is cobordant to *M* if and only if the Chern numbers of *M*′ coincide with those of *M*.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] The theory also extends to real symplectic vector bundles, by the intermediation of compatible almost complex structures.
[src:k-theory/chern-class] In particular, symplectic manifolds have a well-defined Chern class.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] In mathematics, the **Grothendieck group**, or **group of differences**, of a commutative monoid *M* is a certain abelian group.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] This abelian group is constructed from *M* in the most universal way, in the sense that any abelian group containing a homomorphic image of *M* will also contain a homomorphic image of the Grothendieck group of *M*.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The Grothendieck group construction takes its name from a specific case in category theory, introduced by Alexander Grothendieck in his proof of the Grothendieck–Riemann–Roch theorem, which resulted in the development of K-theory.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] This specific case is the monoid of isomorphism classes of objects of an abelian category, with the direct sum as its operation.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Given a commutative monoid M , "the most general" abelian group K that arises from M is to be constructed by introducing inverse elements to all elements of M .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Such an abelian group K always exists; it is called the Grothendieck group of M .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] It is characterized by a certain universal property and can also be concretely constructed from M .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] If M does not have the cancellation property (that is, there exists $a,b$ and c in M such that $a\neq b$ and $ac=bc$ ), then the Grothendieck group K cannot contain M .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] This expresses the fact that any abelian group *A* that contains a homomorphic image of *M* will also contain a homomorphic image of *K*, *K* being the "most general" abelian group containing a homomorphic image of *M*.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] To construct the Grothendieck group *K* of a commutative monoid *M*, one forms the Cartesian product $M\times M$ .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The two coordinates are meant to represent a positive part and a negative part, so $(m_{1},m_{2})$ corresponds to $m_{1}-m_{2}$ in *K*.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Next one defines an equivalence relation on $M\times M$ , such that $(m_{1},m_{2})$ is equivalent to $(n_{1},n_{2})$ if, for some element *k* of *M*, *m*1 + *n*2 + *k* = *m*2 + *n*1 + *k* (the element *k* is necessary because the cancellation law does not hold in all monoids).
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The equivalence class of the element (*m*1, *m*2) is denoted by [(*m*1, *m*2)].
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] One defines *K* to be the set of equivalence classes.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Since the addition operation on *M* × *M* is compatible with our equivalence relation, one obtains an addition on *K*, and *K* becomes an abelian group.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The homomorphism $i:M\to K$ sends the element *m* to [(*m*, 0)].
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Alternatively, the Grothendieck group *K* of *M* can also be constructed using generators and relations: denoting by $(Z(M),+')$ the free abelian group generated by the set *M*, the Grothendieck group *K* is the quotient of $Z(M)$ by the subgroup generated by $\{(x+'y)-'(x+y)\mid x,y\in M\}$ .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] This is known as the "group completion of a semigroup" or "group of fractions of a semigroup".
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] In the language of category theory, any universal construction gives rise to a functor; one thus obtains a functor from the category of commutative monoids to the category of abelian groups which sends the commutative monoid *M* to its Grothendieck group *K*.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] This functor is left adjoint to the forgetful functor from the category of abelian groups to the category of commutative monoids.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] For a commutative monoid *M*, the map *i* : *M* → *K* is injective if and only if *M* has the cancellation property, and it is bijective if and only if *M* is already a group.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The easiest example of a Grothendieck group is the construction of the integers $\mathbb {Z}$ from the (additive) natural numbers $\mathbb {N}$ .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] This defines the integers $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Indeed, this is the usual construction to obtain the integers from the natural numbers.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] See "Construction" under Integers for a more detailed explanation.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] which of course can be identified with the positive rational numbers.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The Grothendieck group is the fundamental construction of K-theory.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The group $K_{0}(M)$ of a compact manifold *M* is defined to be the Grothendieck group of the commutative monoid of all isomorphism classes of vector bundles of finite rank on *M* with the monoid operation given by direct sum.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] This gives a contravariant functor from manifolds to abelian groups.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] This functor is studied and extended in topological K-theory.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The zeroth algebraic K group $K_{0}(R)$ of a (not necessarily commutative) ring *R* is the Grothendieck group of the monoid consisting of isomorphism classes of finitely generated projective modules over *R*, with the monoid operation given by the direct sum.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Then $K_{0}$ is a covariant functor from rings to abelian groups.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The two previous examples are related: consider the case where $R=C^{\infty }(M)$ is the ring of complex-valued smooth functions on a compact manifold *M*.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] In this case the projective *R*-modules are dual to vector bundles over *M* (by the Serre–Swan theorem).
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Another construction that carries the name **Grothendieck group** is the following: Let *R* be a finite-dimensional algebra over some field *k* or more generally an artinian ring.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Then the Grothendieck group $G_{0}(K)$ is an abelian group generated by symbols $[V]$ for any finite-dimensional *K*-vector space *V*.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] In fact, $G_{0}(K)$ is isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z}$ whose generator is the element $[K]$ .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Here, the symbol $[V]$ for a finite-dimensional *K*-vector space *V* is defined as $[V]=\dim _{K}V$ , the dimension of the vector space *V*.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Suppose one has the following short exact sequence of *K*-vector spaces.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Since any short exact sequence of vector spaces splits, it holds that $T\cong V\oplus W$ .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The above equality hence satisfies the condition of the symbol $[V]$ in the Grothendieck group.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Note that any two isomorphic finite-dimensional *K*-vector spaces have the same dimension.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Also, any two finite-dimensional *K*-vector spaces *V* and *W* of same dimension are isomorphic to each other.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] In fact, every finite *n*-dimensional *K*-vector space *V* is isomorphic to $K^{\oplus n}$ .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Hence, every symbol $[V]$ is generated by the element $[K]$ with integer coefficients, which implies that $G_{0}(K)$ is isomorphic to $\mathbb {Z}$ with the generator $[K]$ .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] More generally, let $\mathbb {Z}$ be the set of integers.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The Grothendieck group $G_{0}(\mathbb {Z} )$ is an abelian group generated by symbols $[A]$ for any finitely generated abelian groups *A*.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] One first notes that any finite abelian group *G* satisfies that $[G]=0$ .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The following short exact sequence holds, where the map $\mathbb {Z} \to \mathbb {Z}$ is multiplication by *n*.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The exact sequence implies that $[\mathbb {Z} /n\mathbb {Z} ]=[\mathbb {Z} ]-[\mathbb {Z} ]=0$ , so every cyclic group has its symbol equal to 0.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] This in turn implies that every finite abelian group *G* satisfies $[G]=0$ by the fundamental theorem of finite abelian groups.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Furthermore, the rank of the abelian group satisfies the conditions of the symbol $[A]$ of the Grothendieck group.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Then tensoring with the rational numbers $\mathbb {Q}$ implies the following equation.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Since the above is a short exact sequence of $\mathbb {Q}$ -vector spaces, the sequence splits.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Therefore, one has the following equation.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] On the other hand, one also has the following relation; for more information, see Rank of an abelian group.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The Grothendieck group satisfies a universal property.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] By choosing a suitable basis and writing the corresponding matrices in block triangular form one easily sees that character functions are additive in the above sense.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] By the universal property this gives us a "universal character" $\chi :G_{0}(R)\to \mathrm {Hom} _{K}(R,K)$ such that $\chi ([V])=\chi _{V}$ .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] If $k=\mathbb {C}$ and R is the group ring $\mathbb {C} [G]$ of a finite group G then this character map even gives a natural isomorphism of $G_{0}(\mathbb {C} [G])$ and the character ring $Ch(G)$ .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] In the modular representation theory of finite groups, k can be a field ${\overline {\mathbb {F} _{p}}},$ the algebraic closure of the finite field with *p* elements.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] In this case the analogously defined map that associates to each $k[G]$ -module its Brauer character is also a natural isomorphism $G_{0}({\overline {\mathbb {F} _{p}}}[G])\to \mathrm {BCh} (G)$ onto the ring of Brauer characters.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] In this way Grothendieck groups show up in representation theory.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] This universal property also makes $G_{0}(R)$ the 'universal receiver' of generalized Euler characteristics.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] In fact the Grothendieck group was originally introduced for the study of Euler characteristics.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] A common generalization of these two concepts is given by the Grothendieck group of an exact category ${\mathcal {A}}$ .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Simply put, an exact category is an additive category together with a class of distinguished short sequences *A* → *B* → *C*.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The distinguished sequences are called "exact sequences", hence the name.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The precise axioms for this distinguished class do not matter for the construction of the Grothendieck group.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Every abelian category is an exact category if one just uses the standard interpretation of "exact".
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] This gives the notion of a Grothendieck group in the previous section if one chooses ${\mathcal {A}}:=R{\text{-mod}}$ the category of finitely generated *R*-modules as ${\mathcal {A}}$ .
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] This is really abelian because *R* was assumed to be artinian (and hence noetherian) in the previous section.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] On the other hand, every additive category is also exact if one declares those and only those sequences to be exact that have the form $0\to A\to A\oplus B\to B\to 0$ with the canonical inclusion and projection morphisms.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] Generalizing even further it is also possible to define the Grothendieck group for triangulated categories.
[src:k-theory/grothendieck-group] The construction is essentially similar but uses the relations [*X*] − [*Y*] + [*Z*] = 0 whenever there is a distinguished triangle *X* → *Y* → *Z* → *X*[1].
[src:k-theory/k-theory] In mathematics, **K-theory** is, roughly speaking, the study of a ring generated by vector bundles over a topological space or scheme.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] In algebraic topology, it is a cohomology theory known as topological K-theory.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] In algebra and algebraic geometry, it is referred to as algebraic K-theory.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] It is also a fundamental tool in the field of operator algebras.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] It can be seen as the study of certain kinds of invariants of large matrices.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] K-theory involves the construction of families of *K*-functors that map from topological spaces or schemes, or to be even more general: any object of a homotopy category to associated rings; these rings reflect some aspects of the structure of the original spaces or schemes.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] As with functors to groups in algebraic topology, the reason for this functorial mapping is that it is easier to compute some topological properties from the mapped rings than from the original spaces or schemes.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Examples of results gleaned from the K-theory approach include the Grothendieck–Riemann–Roch theorem, Bott periodicity, the Atiyah–Singer index theorem, and the Adams operations.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] In high energy physics, K-theory and in particular twisted K-theory have appeared in Type II string theory where it has been conjectured that they classify D-branes, Ramond–Ramond field strengths and also certain spinors on generalized complex manifolds.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] In condensed matter physics K-theory has been used to classify topological insulators, superconductors and stable Fermi surfaces.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] For more details, see K-theory (physics).
[src:k-theory/k-theory] The Grothendieck completion of an abelian monoid into an abelian group is a necessary ingredient for defining K-theory since all definitions start by constructing an abelian monoid from a suitable category and turning it into an abelian group through this universal construction.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Equivalence classes in this group should be thought of as formal differences of elements in the abelian monoid.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] This group $(G(A),+)$ is also associated with a monoid homomorphism $i:A\to G(A)$ given by $a\mapsto [(a,0)],$ which has a certain universal property.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] To get a better understanding of this group, consider some equivalence classes of the abelian monoid $(A,+)$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] hence we have an additive inverse $[(b,a)]$ for each $[(a,b)]\in G(A)$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] An illustrative example to look at is the Grothendieck completion of $\mathbb {N}$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] We can see that $G((\mathbb {N} ,+))=(\mathbb {Z} ,+).$ For any pair $(a,b)$ we can find a minimal representative $(a',b')$ by using the invariance under scaling.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] This shows that we should think of the $(a,0)$ as positive integers and the $(0,b)$ as negative integers.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] There are a number of basic definitions of K-theory: two coming from topology and two from algebraic geometry.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Given a compact Hausdorff space X consider the set of isomorphism classes of finite-dimensional vector bundles over X , denoted ${\text{Vect}}(X)$ and let the isomorphism class of a vector bundle $\pi :E\to X$ be denoted $[E]$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] It should be clear that $({\text{Vect}}(X),\oplus )$ is an abelian monoid where the unit is given by the trivial vector bundle $\mathbb {R} ^{0}\times X\to X$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] We can then apply the Grothendieck completion to get an abelian group from this abelian monoid.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] This is called the K-theory of X and is denoted $K^{0}(X)$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] We can use the Serre–Swan theorem and some algebra to get an alternative description of vector bundles over X as projective modules over the ring $C^{0}(X;\mathbb {C} )$ of continuous complex-valued functions.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Then, these can be identified with idempotent matrices in some ring of matrices $M_{n\times n}(C^{0}(X;\mathbb {C} ))$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] We can define equivalence classes of idempotent matrices and form an abelian monoid ${\textbf {Idem}}(X)$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Its Grothendieck completion is also called $K^{0}(X)$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] One of the main techniques for computing the Grothendieck group for topological spaces comes from the Atiyah–Hirzebruch spectral sequence, which makes it very accessible.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] There is an analogous construction by considering vector bundles in algebraic geometry.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] For a Noetherian scheme X there is a set ${\text{Vect}}(X)$ of all isomorphism classes of algebraic vector bundles on X .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Then, as before, the direct sum $\oplus$ of isomorphisms classes of vector bundles is well-defined, giving an abelian monoid $({\text{Vect}}(X),\oplus )$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Then, the Grothendieck group $K^{0}(X)$ is defined by the application of the Grothendieck construction on this abelian monoid.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] In algebraic geometry, the same construction can be applied to algebraic vector bundles over a smooth scheme.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] But, there is an alternative construction for any Noetherian scheme X .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] This gives the Grothendieck-group $K_{0}(X)$ which is isomorphic to $K^{0}(X)$ if X is smooth.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Hence we can use $K_{0}(X)$ for intersection theory.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] The subject can be said to begin with Alexander Grothendieck (1957), who used it to formulate his Grothendieck–Riemann–Roch theorem.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] It takes its name from the German *Klasse*, meaning "class".
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Grothendieck needed to work with coherent sheaves on an algebraic variety *X*.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Rather than working directly with the sheaves, he defined a group using isomorphism classes of sheaves as generators of the group, subject to a relation that identifies any extension of two sheaves with their sum.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] The resulting group is called *K*(*X*) when only locally free sheaves are used, or *G*(*X*) when all are coherent sheaves.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Either of these two constructions is referred to as the Grothendieck group; *K*(*X*) has cohomological behavior and *G*(*X*) has homological behavior.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] If *X* is a smooth variety, the two groups are the same.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] If it is a smooth affine variety, then all extensions of locally free sheaves split, so the group has an alternative definition.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] In topology, by applying the same construction to vector bundles, Michael Atiyah and Friedrich Hirzebruch defined *K*(*X*) for a topological space *X* in 1959, and using the Bott periodicity theorem they made it the basis of an extraordinary cohomology theory.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] It played a major role in the second proof of the Atiyah–Singer index theorem (circa 1962).
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Furthermore, this approach led to a noncommutative K-theory for C*-algebras.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Already in 1955, Jean-Pierre Serre had used the analogy of vector bundles with projective modules to formulate Serre's conjecture, which states that every finitely generated projective module over a polynomial ring is free; this assertion is correct, but was not settled until 20 years later.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] The other historical origin of algebraic K-theory was the work of J.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Whitehead and others on what later became known as Whitehead torsion.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] There followed a period in which there were various partial definitions of *higher K-theory functors*.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Finally, two useful and equivalent definitions were given by Daniel Quillen using homotopy theory in 1969 and 1972.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] A variant was also given by Friedhelm Waldhausen in order to study the *algebraic K-theory of spaces,* which is related to the study of pseudo-isotopies.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Much modern research on higher K-theory is related to algebraic geometry and the study of motivic cohomology.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] The corresponding constructions involving an auxiliary quadratic form received the general name L-theory.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] In string theory, the K-theory classification of Ramond–Ramond field strengths and the charges of stable D-branes was first proposed in 1997.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] The easiest example of the Grothendieck group is the Grothendieck group of a point ${\text{Spec}}(\mathbb {F} )$ for a field $\mathbb {F}$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Since a vector bundle over this space is just a finite dimensional vector space, which is a free object in the category of coherent sheaves, hence projective, the monoid of isomorphism classes is $\mathbb {N}$ corresponding to the dimension of the vector space.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] It is an easy exercise to show that the Grothendieck group is then $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] One important property of the Grothendieck group of a Noetherian scheme X is that it is invariant under reduction, hence $K(X)=K(X_{\text{red}})$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Hence the Grothendieck group of any Artinian $\mathbb {F}$ -algebra is a direct sum of copies of $\mathbb {Z}$ , one for each connected component of its spectrum.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] One of the most commonly used computations of the Grothendieck group is with the computation of $K(\mathbb {P} ^{n})$ for projective space over a field.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] This is because the intersection numbers of a projective X can be computed by embedding $i:X\hookrightarrow \mathbb {P} ^{n}$ and using the push pull formula $i^{*}([i_{*}{\mathcal {E}}]\cdot [i_{*}{\mathcal {F}}])$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] This formula allows one to compute the Grothendieck group of $\mathbb {P} _{\mathbb {F} }^{n}$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] This make it possible to compute the $K_{0}$ or Hirzebruch surfaces.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] In addition, this can be used to compute the Grothendieck group $K(\mathbb {P} ^{n})$ by observing it is a projective bundle over the field $\mathbb {F}$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] One recent technique for computing the Grothendieck group of spaces with minor singularities comes from evaluating the difference between $K^{0}(X)$ and $K_{0}(X)$ , which comes from the fact every vector bundle can be equivalently described as a coherent sheaf.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] This is done using the Grothendieck group of the Singularity category $D_{sg}(X)$ from derived noncommutative algebraic geometry.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] It gives a long exact sequence starting with $\cdots \to K^{0}(X)\to K_{0}(X)\to K_{sg}(X)\to 0$ where the higher terms come from higher K-theory.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Note that vector bundles on a singular X are given by vector bundles $E\to X_{sm}$ on the smooth locus $X_{sm}\hookrightarrow X$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] This makes it possible to compute the Grothendieck group on weighted projective spaces since they typically have isolated quotient singularities.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] For a smooth projective curve C the Grothendieck group is $K_{0}(C)=\mathbb {Z} \oplus {\text{Pic}}(C)$ for Picard group of C .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] This follows from the Brown-Gersten-Quillen spectral sequencepg 72 of algebraic K-theory.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] This spectral sequence has the propertypg 80 $E_{2}^{p,-p}\cong {\text{CH}}^{p}(X)$ for the Chow ring of X , essentially giving the computation of $K_{0}(C)$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Since ${\text{Ext}}_{\text{Ab}}^{1}(\mathbb {Z} ,G)=0$ , we have the sequence of abelian groups above splits, giving the isomorphism.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] This is because reduction gives a generically smooth curve, and all singularities are Cohen-Macaulay.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] One useful application of the Grothendieck-group is to define virtual vector bundles.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] where $C_{Y/X}$ is the conormal bundle of Y in X .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Another useful application of virtual bundles is with the definition of a virtual tangent bundle of an intersection of spaces: Let $Y_{1},Y_{2}\subset X$ be projective subvarieties of a smooth projective variety.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Kontsevich uses this construction in one of his papers.
[src:k-theory/k-theory] In particular, $K_{0}^{G}(C)$ is the Grothendieck group of $\operatorname {Coh} ^{G}(X)$ .
[src:k-theory/k-theory] Specifically, he proved equivariant analogs of fundamental theorems such as the localization theorem.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] In mathematics, **topological K-theory** is a branch of algebraic topology.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] It was founded to study vector bundles on topological spaces, by means of ideas now recognised as (general) K-theory that were introduced by Alexander Grothendieck.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] The early work on topological K-theory is due to Michael Atiyah and Friedrich Hirzebruch.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] Let X be a compact Hausdorff space and $k=\mathbb {R}$ or $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] Then $K_{k}(X)$ is defined to be the Grothendieck group of the commutative monoid of isomorphism classes of finite-dimensional k-vector bundles over X under Whitney sum.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] Tensor product of bundles gives K-theory a commutative ring structure.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] Without subscripts, $K(X)$ usually denotes complex K-theory whereas real K-theory is sometimes written as $KO(X)$ .
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] The remaining discussion is focused on complex K-theory.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] As a first example, note that the K-theory of a point is the integers.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] This is because vector bundles over a point are trivial and thus classified by their rank and the Grothendieck group of the natural numbers is the integers.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] There is also a reduced version of K-theory, ${\widetilde {K}}(X)$ , defined for X a compact pointed space (cf. reduced homology).
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] This reduced theory is intuitively *K*(*X*) modulo trivial bundles.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] It is defined as the group of stable equivalence classes of bundles.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] Two bundles E and F are said to be **stably isomorphic** if there are trivial bundles $\varepsilon _{1}$ and $\varepsilon _{2}$ , so that $E\oplus \varepsilon _{1}\cong F\oplus \varepsilon _{2}$ .
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] This equivalence relation results in a group since every vector bundle can be completed to a trivial bundle by summing with its orthogonal complement.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] Alternatively, ${\widetilde {K}}(X)$ can be defined as the kernel of the map $K(X)\to K(x_{0})\cong \mathbb {Z}$ induced by the inclusion of the base point *x*0 into X.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] K-theory forms a multiplicative (generalized) cohomology theory as follows.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] Negative indices are chosen so that the coboundary maps increase dimension.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] Here $X_{+}$ is X with a disjoint basepoint labeled '+' adjoined.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] Finally, the Bott periodicity theorem as formulated below extends the theories to positive integers.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] In real K-theory there is a similar periodicity, but modulo 8.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] Topological K-theory has been applied in John Frank Adams’ proof of the “Hopf invariant one” problem via Adams operations.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] Adams also proved an upper bound for the number of linearly-independent vector fields on spheres.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] Michael Atiyah and Friedrich Hirzebruch proved a theorem relating the topological K-theory of a finite CW complex X with its rational cohomology.
[src:k-theory/topological-k-theory] There is an algebraic analogue relating the Grothendieck group of coherent sheaves and the Chow ring of a smooth projective variety X .
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The simplest example is the case that the family of vector spaces is constant, i.e., there is a fixed vector space V such that $V(x)=V$ for all x in X : in this case there is a copy of V for each x in X and these copies fit together to form the vector bundle $X\times V$ over X .
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Such vector bundles are said to be *trivial*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] A more complicated (and prototypical) class of examples are the tangent bundles of smooth (or differentiable) manifolds: to every point of such a manifold we attach the tangent space to the manifold at that point.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Tangent bundles are not, in general, trivial bundles.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] For example, the tangent bundle of the sphere is non-trivial by the hairy ball theorem.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] In general, a manifold is said to be parallelizable if, and only if, its tangent bundle is trivial.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Vector bundles are almost always required to be *locally trivial*, which means they are examples of fiber bundles.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Also, the vector spaces are usually required to be over the real or complex numbers, in which case the vector bundle is said to be a real or complex vector bundle (respectively).
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Complex vector bundles can be viewed as real vector bundles with additional structure.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] In the following, we focus on real vector bundles in the category of topological spaces.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The open neighborhood U together with the homeomorphism $\varphi$ is called a **local trivialization** of the vector bundle.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The local trivialization shows that *locally* the map $\pi$ "looks like" the projection of $U\times \mathbb {R} ^{k}$ on U .
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Every fiber $\pi ^{-1}(\{x\})$ is a finite-dimensional real vector space and hence has a dimension $k_{x}$ .
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The local trivializations show that the function $x\to k_{x}$ is locally constant, and is therefore constant on each connected component of X .
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] If $k_{x}$ is equal to a constant k on all of X , then k is called the **rank** of the vector bundle, and E is said to be a **vector bundle of rank k**.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Often the definition of a vector bundle includes that the rank is well defined, so that $k_{x}$ is constant.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Vector bundles of rank 1 are called line bundles, while those of rank 2 are less commonly called plane bundles.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The Cartesian product $X\times \mathbb {R} ^{k}$ , equipped with the projection $X\times \mathbb {R} ^{k}\to X$ , is called the **trivial bundle** of rank k over X .
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] These are called the **transition functions** (or the **coordinate transformations**) of the vector bundle.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] for all $U,V,W$ over which the bundle trivializes satisfying $U\cap V\cap W\neq \emptyset$ .
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Thus the data $(E,X,\pi ,\mathbb {R} ^{k})$ defines a fiber bundle; the additional data of the $g_{UV}$ specifies a ${\text{GL}}(k)$ structure group in which the action on the fiber is the standard action of ${\text{GL}}(k)$ .
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Conversely, given a fiber bundle $(E,X,\pi ,\mathbb {R} ^{k})$ with a ${\text{GL}}(k)$ cocycle acting in the standard way on the fiber $\mathbb {R} ^{k}$ , there is associated a vector bundle.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] This is an example of the fibre bundle construction theorem for vector bundles, and can be taken as an alternative definition of a vector bundle.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] One simple method of constructing vector bundles is by taking subbundles of other vector bundles.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Given a vector bundle $\pi :E\to X$ over a topological space, a subbundle is simply a topological subspace $F\subset E$ for which the restriction $\left.\pi \right|_{F}$ of $\pi$ to F gives $\left.\pi \right|_{F}:F\to X$ the structure of a vector bundle also.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] In this case the fibre $F_{x}\subset E_{x}$ is a vector subspace for every $x\in X$ .
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] A subbundle of a trivial bundle need not be trivial, and indeed every real vector bundle over a compact space can be viewed as a subbundle of a trivial bundle of sufficiently high rank.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] For example, the Möbius band, a non-trivial line bundle over the circle, can be seen as a subbundle of the trivial rank 2 bundle over the circle.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Note that g is determined by f (because $\pi _{1}$ is surjective), and f is then said to **cover *g***.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The class of all vector bundles together with bundle morphisms forms a category.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Restricting to vector bundles for which the spaces are manifolds (and the bundle projections are smooth maps) and smooth bundle morphisms we obtain the category of smooth vector bundles.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Vector bundle morphisms are a special case of the notion of a bundle map between fiber bundles, and are sometimes called **(vector) bundle homomorphisms**.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] A bundle homomorphism from $E_{1}$ to $E_{2}$ with an inverse which is also a bundle homomorphism (from $E_{2}$ to $E_{1}$ ) is called a **(vector) bundle isomorphism**, and then $E_{1}$ and $E_{2}$ are said to be **isomorphic** vector bundles.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] An isomorphism of a (rank k ) vector bundle E over X with the trivial bundle (of rank k over X ) is called a **trivialization** of E , and E is then said to be **trivial** (or **trivializable**).
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The definition of a vector bundle shows that any vector bundle is **locally trivial**.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] We can also consider the category of all vector bundles over a fixed base space X .
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] As morphisms in this category we take those morphisms of vector bundles whose map on the base space is the identity map on X .
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] A vector bundle morphism between vector bundles $\pi _{1}:E_{1}\rightarrow X_{1}$ and $\pi _{2}:E_{2}\rightarrow X_{2}$ covering a map g from $X_{1}$ to $X_{2}$ can also be viewed as a vector bundle morphism over $X_{1}$ from $E_{1}$ to the pullback bundle $g^{*}E_{2}$ .
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Given a vector bundle π: *E* → *X* and an open subset *U* of *X*, we can consider **sections** of π on *U*, i.e. continuous functions *s*: *U* → *E* where the composite π ∘ *s* is such that (π ∘ *s*)(*u*) = *u* for all *u* in *U*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] A section over *U* is an assignment, to every point *p* of *U*, a vector from the vector space fibre above *p*, in a continuous manner.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] As an example, a section of the tangent bundle of a differential manifold is the same as a vector field on that manifold.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Let *F*(*U*) be the set of all sections on *U*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] *F*(*U*) always contains at least one element, namely the **zero section**: the function *s* that maps every element *x* of *U* to the zero element of the vector space π−1({*x*}).
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] With the pointwise addition and scalar multiplication of sections, *F*(*U*) becomes itself a real vector space.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The collection of these vector spaces is a sheaf of vector spaces on *X*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] If *s* is an element of *F*(*U*) and f : *U* → **R** is a continuous map, then their product f*s* (pointwise scalar multiplication) is in *F*(*U*).
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] This shows that *F*(*U*) is a module over the ring of continuous real-valued functions on *U*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Furthermore, if O*X* denotes the structure sheaf of continuous real-valued functions on *X*, then *F* becomes a sheaf of O*X*-modules.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Not every sheaf of O*X*-modules arises in this fashion from a vector bundle: only the locally free ones do.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Even more: the category of real vector bundles on *X* is equivalent to the category of locally free and finitely generated sheaves of O*X*-modules.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] So we can think of the category of real vector bundles on *X* as sitting inside the category of sheaves of O*X*-modules; this latter category is abelian, so this is where we can compute kernels and cokernels of morphisms of vector bundles.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] A rank *n* vector bundle is trivial if and only if it has *n* linearly independent global sections.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Most operations on vector spaces can be extended to vector bundles by performing the vector space operation *fiberwise*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] For example, if *E* is a vector bundle over *X*, then there is a bundle *E** over *X*, called the **dual bundle**, whose fiber at *x* ∈ *X* is the dual vector space (*Ex*)*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Formally *E** can be defined as the set of pairs (*x*, φ), where *x* ∈ *X* and φ ∈ (*E**x*)*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The dual bundle is locally trivial because the dual space of the inverse of a local trivialization of *E* is a local trivialization of *E**: the key point here is that the operation of taking the dual vector space is functorial.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] There are many functorial operations which can be performed on pairs of vector spaces (over the same field), and these extend straightforwardly to pairs of vector bundles *E*, *F* on *X* (over the given field).
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Each of these operations is a particular example of a general feature of bundles: that many operations that can be performed on the category of vector spaces can also be performed on the category of vector bundles in a functorial manner.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] This is made precise in the language of smooth functors.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] An operation of a different nature is the **pullback bundle** construction.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Given a vector bundle *E* → *Y* and a continuous map *f*: *X* → *Y* one can "pull back" *E* to a vector bundle *f*E* over *X*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The fiber over a point *x* ∈ *X* is essentially just the fiber over *f*(*x*) ∈ *Y*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Hence, Whitney summing *E* ⊕ *F* can be defined as the pullback bundle of the diagonal map from *X* to *X* × *X* where the bundle over *X* × *X* is *E* × *F*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Vector bundles are often given more structure.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] For instance, vector bundles may be equipped with a vector bundle metric.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Usually this metric is required to be positive definite, in which case each fibre of *E* becomes a Euclidean space.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] A vector bundle with a complex structure corresponds to a complex vector bundle, which may also be obtained by replacing real vector spaces in the definition with complex ones and requiring that all mappings be complex-linear in the fibers.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] More generally, one can typically understand the additional structure imposed on a vector bundle in terms of the resulting reduction of the structure group of a bundle.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Vector bundles over more general topological fields may also be used.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] If instead of a finite-dimensional vector space, the fiber *F* is taken to be a Banach space then a **Banach bundle** is obtained.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] are continuous mappings of Banach manifolds.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] In the corresponding theory for C*p* bundles, all mappings are required to be C*p*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Vector bundles are special fiber bundles, those whose fibers are vector spaces and whose cocycle respects the vector space structure.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] More general fiber bundles can be constructed in which the fiber may have other structures; for example sphere bundles are fibered by spheres.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] A vector bundle (*E*, *p*, *M*) is **smooth**, if *E* and *M* are smooth manifolds, p: *E* → *M* is a smooth map, and the local trivializations are diffeomorphisms.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Depending on the required degree of smoothness, there are different corresponding notions of *Cp* bundles, infinitely differentiable *C*∞-bundles and real analytic *C*ω-bundles.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] In this section we will concentrate on *C*∞-bundles.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The most important example of a *C*∞-vector bundle is the tangent bundle (*TM*, π*TM*, *M*) of a *C*∞-manifold *M*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] A smooth vector bundle can be characterized by the fact that it admits transition functions as described above which are *smooth* functions on overlaps of trivializing charts *U* and *V*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] is a smooth function into the matrix group GL(k,**R**), which is a Lie group.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The *C*∞-vector bundles (*E*, *p*, *M*) have a very important property not shared by more general *C*∞-fibre bundles.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Namely, the tangent space *Tv*(*E**x*) at any *v* ∈ *E**x* can be naturally identified with the fibre *E**x* itself.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The total space *E* of any smooth vector bundle carries a natural vector field *V**v* := vl*v**v*, known as the *canonical vector field*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] More formally, *V* is a smooth section of (*TE*, π*TE*, *E*), and it can also be defined as the infinitesimal generator of the Lie-group action $(t,v)\mapsto e^{tv}$ given by the fibrewise scalar multiplication.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The canonical vector field *V* characterizes completely the smooth vector bundle structure in the following manner.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] does not depend on the choice of the linear covariant derivative ∇ on *M*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The zero set of *V* is a smooth submanifold of *E* whose codimension is equal to the rank of *C*v(*V*).
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] Conversely, if *E* is any smooth manifold and *V* is a smooth vector field on *E* satisfying 1–4, then there is a unique vector bundle structure on *E* whose canonical vector field is *V*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] For any smooth vector bundle (*E*, *p*, *M*) the total space *TE* of its tangent bundle (*TE*, π*TE*, *E*) has a natural secondary vector bundle structure (*TE*, *p**, *TM*), where *p** is the push-forward of the canonical projection *p*: *E* → *M*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The vector bundle operations in this secondary vector bundle structure are the push-forwards +*: *T*(*E* × *E*) → *TE* and λ*: *TE* → *TE* of the original addition +: *E* × *E* → *E* and scalar multiplication λ: *E* → *E*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] KO-theory is a version of this construction which considers real vector bundles.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] K-theory with compact supports can also be defined, as well as higher K-theory groups.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The famous periodicity theorem of Raoul Bott asserts that the K-theory of any space *X* is isomorphic to that of the *S*2*X*, the double suspension of *X*.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] In algebraic geometry, one considers the K-theory groups consisting of coherent sheaves on a scheme *X*, as well as the K-theory groups of vector bundles on the scheme with the above equivalence relation.
[src:k-theory/vector-bundle] The two constructs are naturally isomorphic provided that the underlying scheme is smooth.
